14:28:06.313 [INFO] # Design constraints for a household assistant

14:28:06.313 [INFO] Before I let this idea become a "platform," I want to write down the constraints that make it worth building at all.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] If I do not do this early, the project will drift toward the usual failure modes: too much scope, too much enchantment, too much surveillance posture, too much hidden complexity, and not enough usefulness on an ordinary Wednesday.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 1. It has to reduce load, not create a new hobby

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The assistant is not allowed to become another dependent system that needs constant tuning, prompting, babysitting, dashboard grooming, or ritual maintenance just to justify its existence.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] If it saves time only after I spend three weekends integrating and curating everything, then it is a workshop project, not household infrastructure.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The test is simple:

14:28:06.313 [INFO] - does it make this week lighter
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - does it help on a tired day, not just on an ambitious day
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - would Petra describe it as useful rather than "one more thing you are currently very interested in"

14:28:06.313 [INFO] That last one is brutal but fair.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 2. Local-first is the default, not the slogan

14:28:06.313 [INFO] Family life contains too many things that should not casually become cloud training slurry or vendor residue.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] School notes, kindergarten messages, household routines, health-adjacent patterns, private tensions, children's details, and all the soft context that makes a home function should stay local unless there is a very clear reason not to.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] This does not mean some cloud component can never exist. It means the burden of proof runs in one direction:

14:28:06.313 [INFO] - local by default
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - export intentionally
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - keep the sensitive raw material close to home
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - never pretend "temporary upload" is the same thing as no exposure

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The assistant should earn trust partly by where it does not send things.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 3. Household consent beats technical possibility

14:28:06.313 [INFO] Just because something can be sensed, transcribed, linked, summarized, or inferred does not mean it should be.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] I do not want to build a family panopticon decorated as convenience.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] That means no ambient capture just because it is available.
14:28:06.313 [INFO] No auto-listening room fantasy.
14:28:06.313 [INFO] No creepy memory model that quietly turns domestic life into permanent searchable evidence.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] If the household system knows something sensitive, it should be because a person deliberately placed it there for a clear reason. The assistant should help with explicit notes, chosen reminders, visible schedules, and bounded summaries more than with passive extraction.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] Useful beats magical.
14:28:06.313 [INFO] Visible beats spooky.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 4. It must preserve lane boundaries

14:28:06.313 [INFO] One of the biggest temptations in any "assistant" system is to merge everything because merged context looks smart.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] In practice, merged context is how you leak the wrong thing into the wrong lane.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] My life is not one context. It is overlapping contexts with different trust rules:

14:28:06.313 [INFO] - family and children
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - Petra's work and bureau-adjacent requests
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - my day job
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - consulting clients
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - startup experiments
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - private health and personal notes
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - hobby clutter that should not suddenly become strategic input

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The assistant should be able to notice relationships across those lanes without flattening them into one big context soup. It should help me navigate boundaries, not erase them.

14:28:06.313 [WARN] ## 5. It has to be interruption-friendly

14:28:06.313 [INFO] This system is being designed for a life made of fragments.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] That means it has to work for:

14:28:06.313 [INFO] - ten-minute resumptions
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - half-finished notes
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - postponed tasks
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - "what was I doing here" moments
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - week plans broken by illness, school surprises, or work fires

14:28:06.313 [INFO] A lot of productivity tooling quietly assumes clean context and long focus blocks. That is not my life. The assistant has to help on broken terrain.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] If it only shines when I am already organized and well-rested, it is ornamental.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 6. Quiet competence matters more than personality

14:28:06.313 [INFO] I do not need a chirpy sidekick.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] Tone matters, but mainly in the negative sense: the assistant should not sound theatrical, manipulative, overeager, or weirdly proud of ordinary actions. It should not manufacture intimacy. It should not pressure me to engage with it like it is a pet, a coach, or a social app.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The ideal tone is calm, direct, and slightly boring in the best possible way.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] When it helps, I should feel supported.
14:28:06.313 [INFO] When it is absent, I should feel nothing.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] That is a compliment.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 7. It must explain itself when the stakes are real

14:28:06.313 [INFO] Invisible automation is only pleasant while everything is low-risk.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] As soon as the system is crossing a boundary, making a commitment, inferring intent from messy notes, or omitting something that could matter, I need it to be legible.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] Not verbose. Legible.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] I want to know:

14:28:06.313 [INFO] - what it knows from source
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - what it inferred
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - where the uncertainty is
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - why it chose this summary, draft, or reminder
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - when it needs confirmation instead of pretending confidence

14:28:06.313 [INFO] If I cannot inspect the reasoning in important cases, then trust will decay the first time it gets something subtly wrong.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 8. Good enough beats universal

14:28:06.313 [INFO] I need to keep remembering that the first useful version is probably narrow and unglamorous.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The goal is not "an assistant for all of life."
14:28:06.313 [INFO] The goal is probably something more like:

14:28:06.313 [INFO] - one weekly household synthesis that is actually worth reading
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - one reliable place for active reminders and pending follow-ups
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - one way to resume stalled work without rereading half my own history
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - one careful split between family-safe and lab-only context

14:28:06.313 [INFO] That is already a lot.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] If I try to solve voice, omnichannel capture, generalized planning, family displays, agentic action, and productization all at once, I will build a shrine to scope instead of a useful system.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 9. It should improve the real week, not the imagined future week

14:28:06.313 [INFO] I am unusually vulnerable to elegant future systems.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] I can always picture the integrated version: better routing, smarter memory, cleaner dashboards, structured entities, ambient surfaces, graceful summaries, all of it.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] That future picture is not useless, but it is dangerous.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The real question is more grounded:

14:28:06.313 [INFO] - what helps this week
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - what helps when someone is sick
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - what helps when Petra needs something fast
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - what helps when work is noisy and I have twenty minutes
14:28:06.313 [INFO] - what still works when I am too tired to appreciate the architecture

14:28:06.313 [WARN] If a feature only pays off in the imaginary life where I have spare cognitive bandwidth and uninterrupted weekends, it belongs on the parking lot, not in the assistant core.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## 10. The assistant should make me more present, not more optimized

14:28:06.313 [INFO] This is the hardest one to evaluate and probably the most important.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The system is succeeding if it helps me keep promises, protect attention, and stop leaking important obligations through fatigue.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] It is failing if it turns my family into a logistics problem, my hobbies into productivity units, or my own body into a dashboard with guilt attached.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] I want leverage, not colonization.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] That is the line.

14:28:06.313 [INFO] ## Working definition

14:28:06.313 [INFO] For now, the shortest honest definition I have is this:

14:28:06.313 [INFO] The assistant is a local-first continuity system for a busy household and overloaded working life.

14:28:06.314 [INFO] It should help me remember, resume, separate, and follow through.

14:28:06.314 [INFO] It should not perform omniscience.
14:28:06.314 [INFO] It should not flatten trust boundaries.
14:28:06.314 [INFO] It should not demand to become the center of the house.

14:28:06.314 [INFO] If it becomes calm infrastructure, it has a future.
14:28:06.314 [INFO] If it becomes another clever appetite, it does not.

